issues.short_description:
`core.PathExists` in `src/core/utils.go` is a thin alias for `fs.PathExists` and is marked with a TODO to remove and migrate.

Code reference:
- `src/core/utils.go:530-534`:
  ```go
  // PathExists is an alias to fs.PathExists.
  // TODO(peterebden): Remove and migrate everything over.
  func PathExists(filename string) bool {
      return fs.PathExists(filename)
  }
  ```
- Numerous call sites across `core`, `build`, `test`, `cache`, etc (see `grep "core.PathExists"`).

The remote CAS directory builder uses a `hasChild` helper that linearly scans `Directory.Directories` on each call, even though a `dirs` map exists.

Code reference:
- `src/remote/utils.go:434-452`:
  ```go
  func (b *dirBuilder) dir(dir, child string) *pb.Directory {
      ...
      // TODO(peterebden): The linear scan in hasChild is a bit suboptimal, we should
      //                   really use the dirs map to determine this.
      if child != "" && !hasChild(d, child) {
          d.Directories = append(d.Directories, &pb.DirectoryNode{Name: child})
      }
      return d
  }
  ```

The command replacement logic in `src/core/command_replacements.go` relies heavily on `panic` and a deferred `recover` to propagate errors, with an explicit TODO to "get rid of all the panics". This pattern complicates control flow and makes error paths harder to follow.

Code references:
- `src/core/command_replacements.go:121-128`:
  ```go
  // TODO(peterebden): should probably just get rid of all the panics and thread errors around properly.
  defer func() {
      if r := recover(); r != nil {
          err = fmt.Errorf("%s", r)
          log.Debug(string(debug.Stack()))
      }
  }()
  ```
- Multiple `panic(...)` calls in the same file (e.g. when parsing labels, hashing outputs, etc.).
